# MCP Server Assignments for ic-knowledge-graph

## Step 1 — Always check ARANGO_MODE first

Before any ArangoDB or Entity Resolution MCP operation, read `.env` in the
project root and check the value of `ARANGO_MODE`.

```
ARANGO_MODE=REMOTE  →  use the remote servers (default)
ARANGO_MODE=LOCAL   →  use the local servers (Docker on localhost:8530)
```

## Step 2 — Use the correct server pair

| ARANGO_MODE | ArangoDB server | Entity Resolution server |
|---|---|---|
| `REMOTE` | `user-arangodb-ic-knowledge-graph-mcp` | `user-ic-knowledge-graph-arango-entity-resolution-mcp` |
| `LOCAL` | `user-arangodb-ic-knowledge-graph-local-mcp` | `user-ic-knowledge-graph-arango-entity-resolution-local-mcp` |

Local servers connect to `http://localhost:8530`. The local Docker container must
be running before using them (see E2E test fixture in `tests/conftest.py`).

## Step 3 — Warn on mismatch

If the user issues a DB command and `ARANGO_MODE` differs from what you expected,
say so explicitly:
> "`.env` has `ARANGO_MODE=LOCAL` — I will use the local MCP servers.
>  Make sure Docker is running and the container is healthy."

## Never use for this project

These servers belong to other projects and must not be used here:

- `user-arangodb-dnb-sharded-amp-mcp`
- `user-arangodb-fraud-intelligence-mcp`
- `user-arangodb-risk-intelligence-mcp`
- `user-dnb-er`
- `user-fraud-intelligence-arango-entity-resolution-mcp`
- `user-entity-resolution-demo`

## Switching modes

To switch from REMOTE to LOCAL (or back), edit `.env`:
```
ARANGO_MODE=LOCAL
```
No Cursor restart is required — the MCP servers for both modes are always
registered and ready. The agent routes at call time based on `.env`.
